MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the Service Propulsion System lesson, {{profileName}}!
You are currently in a stable orbit around Earth, still attached to the S-IVB launch vehicle.
We will first detach from the S-IVB, then look at the systems needed to control the Service Propulsion System (SPS).
This will go through the basic operations. I recommend checking the Flight Manual for details.
To separate from the S-IVB, all we need to do is to press the CSM/LV Sep push button on MDC-1. It is a covered button so you need to open the cover first.
If everything went well, you should now be separated from the launch vehicle.
Go to the EXTERNAL view and you should see the CSM orbiting just in front of the LV. Usually, more steps are needed to safely do this, but for this lesson this is sufficient.
Go back into the cockpit, as we will take a look at the different systems needed to operate and check the Service Propulsion System (SPS).
The Service Propulsion System (SPS) consists of a helium pressurization system, a propellant feed system, a propellant gauging and utilization system, and a rocket engine.
The restartable rocket engine has a nominal thrust of 20,500 lbs (91.2 kN) and can be gimbaled using the Thrust Vector Control (TVC).
The oxidizer and the fuel in the Service Propulsion System (SPS) is used to ignite and generate thrust in the SPS engine.
The total propellant supply is contained within four similar tanks; an oxidizer storage tank, oxidizer sump tank, fuel storage tank, and fuel sump tank.
It is pressurized with Helium at 175 psi to push the substances into the engine thrust chamber.
The Helium valves can be controlled using the SPS He VLV A/B switches on MDC-3. Set SPS He VLV A to OFF (middle position).
The A and B system is controlled by the dV THRUST A and B switches on MDC-1. Arm the dV THRUST A system now.
Leave the protective cover open. If you close it, the switch will also be pushed into the down position.

The SPS He Vlv MNA and MNB switches applies power from the MNA and MNB main buses to the A and B helium valves switches, their talkback indicator, and the dV THRUST NORMAL A/B switch for injector pre-valve A/B.
The PILOT VLVS MNA and MNB supplies 28 vdc to the dV THRUST NORMAL switch A/B. These circuit breakers needs to be closed to operate system A and system B.
The SPS He VLV talkback indicators show if the Helium valves are open (gray) or closed (barberpole). With SYS A powered and armed, set the SPS He VLV A to ON.
Nnotice the valve is opened. Set it back to AUTO.
AUTO will control the valves automatically by the thrust on/off logic and is the normal position.
Above these controls, you will find the PROPELLANT UTILIZATION & GAUGING SUBSYSTEM system, found just below the SPS QUANTITY label.
The PROPELLANT UTILIZATION & GAUGING SUBSYSTEM (PUGS) is used to monitor the propellant. The Service Propulsion System (SPS) has a normal ratio of fuel:oxidizer at 1:1.6 initially.
When both the fuel and the oxidizer levels are the same, the system is balanced.
The OXID UNBAL gauge shows the balance of the system. If it reads 0, the system is balanced. This is the ratio between the OXID and FUEL percentage above

If it is unbalanced, the OXID UNBAL gauge will indicate a value on either the INCR or DECR side. Propellant utilization valves can be used to correct any unbalancing. It will change the mixture-ratio to balance the system.
Again, the Service Propulsion System (SPS) engine is a restartable engine and is the primary source of thrust after S-IVB separation.
There are two pairs of engine injector valves named the bipropellant valve system A/B. The engine is ignited by opening one or both of these, and is shut down by closing the opened valve(s).
When opened, the engine will throttle at max thrust for the duration of the burn.
Each engine ignition requires nitrogen from the bipropellant valve system in use to start. At the launchpad, this is filled to 2500 psia for each system.
This will need to be at least 400 psi for the system in use. In addition, each ignition will require 50 psi of Nitrogen from the bipropellant valve system A and/or B.
The SPS instrumentation gauges on the upper part of MDC-3 lets you see the status of the Service Propulsion System (SPS) systems. Two gauges are available, each with two indicators.
The two gauges can show the temperature, Helium and Nitrogen levels, and the Fuel/Oxidizer levels. The He/N2 line can be selected using the SPS PRESS IND switch. Set this to N2B (down position)
This configures the left SPS gauge to show the N₂ pressure of N₂ tank B. You can configure it to show the SPS He, N₂ tank 1 or the N₂ tank 2 pressure.
Most of the controls to ignite the SPS engine are located on MDC-1.

Either or both the A or B SPS injector valve systems need to be armed to ignite the engine. The protected dV THRUST A/B switches on MDC-1 switch is used to ARM the control logic for the engine injector valves A/B.
Verify that the dV THRUST A system is still armed.
Ensure SPS Pc is selected for monitoring on the LV/SPS Pc gauge.
The LV/SPS Pc gauge shows the chamber pressure if the LV/SPS IND switch below is in Pc, and it's usually 100% during a burn.

If the SPS propellant is less than 50%, the fuel might be floating around in the tank due to free fall gravity. Therefore, before igniting the engine, the propellant needs to be settled down in the tanks.
This is done using the DIRECT ULLAGE button on MDC-1, or using the forward translation thrusters. We won't need to do this now.
The engine is ignited in three different ways after being armed and ready.
The primary method is to use the Computer and the CMC dV mode, using Program 30 and Program 40.

The secondary method is to use the Stabilization and Control System (SCS) and the SCS dV mode. The SC CONT switch needs to be in SCS, and the Entry Monitoring System (EMS) needs to be in dV mode with the EMS dV/RANGE set to a number above 0 ft/s. When this is set, the THRUST ON button is pressed to ignite the engine.

The third method is to use the SPS thrust Direct On mode, and is considered as the backup mode. The SPS THRUST switch is set to DIRECT ON to ignite the engine, and NORMAL to shut it down. The EMS can optionally be used to detect dV changes.
Let's try to use the third option now. Set the SPS Thrust Direct On switch to DIRECT ON. This will ignite the engine and start the burn.
Turn this OFF as soon as possible to shut down the engine again.
This covered the basics of the Service Propulsion System (SPS) and some of its features. Later lessons will continue to dive deeper into the SPS.
Congratulations on completing the SPS lesson, this concludes the lesson.

Title: Lesson 6 - Service Propulsion
Description: The Service Propulsion system is used to do large delta V changes when in Orbit. The huge bell shaped engine on the Service Module is the nozzle for this system.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

The service propulsion subsystem provides the impulse for all X-axis velocity changes (ΔVs) throughout a mission and the SPS abort capability after the launch escape tower is jettisoned. The SPS consists of a helium pressurization system, a propellant feed system, a propellant gauging and utilization system, and a rocket engine.

In this lesson, we will learn how it works, and how to operate it.

Good luck!
